  3. id=978 | title=ATTENTION-DEFICIT/HYPERACTIVITY DISORDER | type= | description=ATTENTION-DEFICIT/HYPERACTIVITY DISORDER (ADHD) is a neurodevelopmental disorder characterized by persistent patterns of inattention, hyperactivity, and impulsivity that interfere with functioning or development. It typically emerges in childhood and can persist into adolescence and adulthood. The core symptoms of ADHD include difficulty sustaining attention, being easily distracted, forgetfulness in daily activities, failure to follow through on instructions, and challenges with organizing tasks and activities—hallmarks of inattention. Hyperactivity manifests as excessive movement, fidgeting, inability to remain seated when expected, and talking excessively, while impulsivity is observed through hasty actions without forethought, interrupting others, and difficulty waiting for one’s turn.

ADHD is recognized as one of the most common neurodevelopmental disorders in children and adolescents, though it frequently continues into adulthood, affecting individuals across the lifespan. The disorder is believed to arise from a combination of genetic, neurological, and environmental factors. Neuroimaging studies have shown differences in brain structure and function, particularly in regions associated with executive functions such as attention regulation, impulse control, and motor activity.

Diagnosis is based on clinical evaluation using standardized criteria, such as those outlined in the Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders (DSM-5), which require that symptoms be present before age 12, occur in multiple settings (e.g., home and school), and result in significant impairment in social, academic, or occupational functioning. There are three primary presentations of ADHD: predominantly inattentive presentation, predominantly hyperactive-impulsive presentation, and combined presentation, depending on the predominant symptoms exhibited.

Treatment often involves a multimodal approach, including behavioral interventions, educational accommodations, and medication. Stimulant medications, such as methylphenidate and amphetamines, are commonly prescribed and have been shown to effectively reduce symptoms in many individuals. Non-stimulant medications and psychotherapeutic strategies, such as cognitive-behavioral therapy, may also be used, especially when stimulants are not effective or well-tolerated.

Despite its challenges, many individuals with ADHD develop effective coping strategies and achieve success in academic, professional, and personal domains, particularly with early identification and appropriate support. Public awareness and understanding of ADHD continue to grow, helping to reduce stigma and improve access to care. Overall, ADHD is a complex but manageable condition that requires a comprehensive, individualized approach to diagnosis and treatment.
