  17. id=885 | title=AUTISM SPECTRUM DISORDER | type= | description=Autism Spectrum Disorder (ASD) is a neurodevelopmental disorder characterized by persistent challenges in social communication and interaction, along with restricted, repetitive patterns of behavior, interests, or activities. The condition exhibits significant clinical and genetic heterogeneity, with symptoms and severity varying widely among individuals. Core features include difficulties in verbal and nonverbal communication, reduced social reciprocity, and the presence of stereotyped motor movements or rigid adherence to routines.

Genetic research has identified several biological underpinnings associated with ASD. Notably, deletions in the chromosomal region 18q12.2, which encompasses the CELF4 gene, have been linked to the disorder. The CELF4 gene encodes an RNA-binding protein involved in neuronal development and synaptic function, suggesting that disruptions in this gene may contribute to the neurodevelopmental abnormalities observed in ASD. Consequently, ASD has been specifically associated with deletions encompassing the CELF4 gene, reinforcing its genetic basis and highlighting the role of specific genomic regions in disease etiology.

In addition to rare structural variants such as copy number deletions, common genetic variation also plays a significant role in ASD susceptibility. Genome-wide association studies (GWAS) have been conducted to identify single nucleotide polymorphisms associated with ASD, and the resulting summary statistics have been utilized in polygenic risk score (PRS) analyses. These approaches help quantify the cumulative effect of many common genetic variants across the genome, providing insights into the heritability of ASD and enabling risk prediction in research settings.

Collectively, Autism Spectrum Disorder arises from a complex interplay of genetic factors, including both rare mutations—such as those affecting the 18q12.2 region and the CELF4 gene—and common variants analyzed through GWAS and PRS methodologies. While the precise mechanisms linking these genetic alterations to behavioral phenotypes remain under investigation, current evidence underscores the importance of synaptic regulation and neural circuit development in the pathophysiology of ASD. Ongoing research continues to refine the genetic architecture of the disorder, aiming to improve early diagnosis, stratification, and personalized intervention strategies.

